    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if i want to get more of that sour flavor, i should keep it on the cooler side to favor the lactobacilli? also i'm curious about the starch breakdown—how do the enzymes actually turn the flour into food for these microbes?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Keeping the starter on a cooler side (around 40-55°F/4-13°C) can indeed promote a more pronounced sour flavor and increased lactobacilli activity. This cooler environment enhances the bacterium's ability to ferment existing lactic acid, rather than relying on the yeast's initial fermentation process.\n\nRegarding starch breakdown, it's primarily the enzymes present in the flour that convert starches into fermentable sugars. These enzymes, such as amylase and glucoamylase, break down the complex starches into simple ones like glucose, fructose, and galactose. This process typically occurs during the autolyse phase (after a starter is fed and before mixing), allowing the enzymes to hydrolyze starches without the yeast's involvement. Then, the yeast ferments the resulting sugars, producing CO2 and ethyl acetate, which contribute to the sour flavor.",
      "source": "target",
