      "content": "Yes, it's indeed a complex ecosystem, and it's remarkable how yeast and bacteria can work together in a harmonious way despite being from different strains and kingdoms. \n\nOne of the most common ways people mess up the balance is by over-feeding their starter, causing the yeast population to overgrow and crowd out the lactobacilli. This can happen when a starter is fed too frequently or large amounts of flour are added. As a result, the starter may become too acidic and specify to yeast, or it may sit too long at room temperature, favoring yeast domination. A moderate feeding schedule and careful temperature monitoring can help maintain the delicate balance between these microorganisms.",
